1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:21,000
Today is Saturday, March 9, 2013. My name is Willie Griffin and I am a research associate with the Southern Oral History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

3
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:31,000
I am with Willie Griffin John Bishop and Albany Georgia on the campus of Albany State University University to conduct an interview for the Civil Rights History Project,

4
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:39,000
which is a joint undertaking of the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

5
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:44,000
We are here today with Mrs. Mary Jenkins who played a role in the local Albany movement.

6
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:50,000
Thank you so much, Ms. Jenkins, for being here and agreeing to share your story with the Civil Rights History Project.

7
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:53,000
Thank you for accepting me.

8
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:58,000
Okay, can we begin with you stating your full name, date and place of birth?

9
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:06,000
My name is Mary Francis Jenkins.

10
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:08,000
I just missed that, I was in that.

11
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:10,000
And you were born when?

12
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:13,000
I was born in Waycross, Georgia, where county?

13
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:16,000
Okay, I was the date of your birth.

14
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:18,000
Oh, August 12, 1928.

15
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:20,000
Okay, it's August 12, 1928.

16
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:26,000
So you were born in Waycross, Georgia, how long did you spend in Waycross, Georgia before the year?

17
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:33,000
Well, not many years. When I was very young, I lived in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.

18
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:41,000
My father was killed in automobile accident on Georgia highway.

19
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:47,000
And when my mother remarried, we moved to Albany, Georgia.

20
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:51,000
Okay. And how old were you when you moved to Albany, Georgia?

21
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:53,000
When I moved to Albany, Georgia? Yeah, about how old were you?

22
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:56,000
Oh, I was about eight or nine.

23
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:59,000
I remember I entered the fourth grade.

24
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:06,000
Okay, okay. So when you came to Albany, what was the city like?

25
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:08,000
Do you remember anything about it?

26
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:11,000
Well, yes, I remember a lot about it.

27
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:12,000
Okay.

28
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:14,000
I grew up in the Jim Crow era.

29
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:15,000
Okay.

30
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:18,000
I sat in the balcony of the Albany movie theater.

31
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:21,000
I drank from the separate water fountain.

32
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:26,000
So I know a lot about segregation as it existed.

33
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:32,000
I remember when I was very young walking through the crests, ten-sens total.

34
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:35,000
And my mother was holding tightly to my hand.

35
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:42,000
And a little white boy just about my age walked up and squirted a water pistol in my face.

36
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:47,000
And I tried desperately to get away from my mother so that I could catch him.

37
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:51,000
But she kept saying, you can't.

38
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:56,000
And pretty much you can't has followed my life.

39
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:02,000
You know, when my daughter was three years old, I took her to Teapar.

40
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:06,000
And she saw some white children getting on buses.

41
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:09,000
Well, they were rides for them.

42
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:13,000
And she said, money, I want to ride on that.

43
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:16,000
And I had to say the same thing to her.

44
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:21,000
That my mother said to me, you can't.

45
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:24,000
And she turned around and beat her little fist against me.

46
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:29,000
And she said, you don't want me to ride.

47
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:32,000
How was I to explain the system to her?

48
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:38,000
So that meant that I had to take the blame.

49
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:41,000
Okay.

50
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:46,000
So, do you think, I mean, do you know that your mother was probably trying to protect you?

51
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:49,000
Oh, definitely, definitely.

52
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:57,000
Anytime that we were in some sort of white situation, she was clinging, you know, to me.

53
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:00,000
And I knew that.

54
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:04,000
So, beyond those, what else do you remember?

55
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:10,000
Those memories of I should mother, what else do you remember about her in terms of her bringing you up

56
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:15,000
and the other mess, and she tried instilling you as a person?

57
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:23,000
Oh, well, she, well, one thing I do know, she definitely wanted me to have a good education.

58
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:27,000
She never finished high school.

59
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:28,000
Okay.

60
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:39,000
And so she was definitely trying to convince me that education is the key to everything you want.

61
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:44,000
And your, so what was your mother primarily at homemaker?

62
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:46,000
She was primarily at homemaker.

63
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:50,000
Okay. And you said she was remarried, so your stepfather, what was his profession?

64
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:55,000
Stepfather worked on the (Atlantic) Coast Line Railroad.

65
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:56,000
Okay.

66
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:57,000
What position?

67
00:04:57,000 --> 00:04:59,000
So we always could travel.

68
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Oh, okay.

69
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:01,000
Half-fat.

70
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:05,000
That's always good.

71
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:09,000
So, the schools that you attended, what was the first schools that you attended?

72
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:11,000
Madison High School.

73
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:19,000
Madison High School was all segregated, all black school that I attended.

74
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:27,000
And of course, by being a segregated school, we received hand-me-down books.

75
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:33,000
The equipment was not the modern kind for that day.

76
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:37,000
But I think we had the best teachers in the world.

77
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:40,000
Who were some of the most memorable teachers?

78
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:41,000
Oh, okay.

79
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:48,000
Miss Ruth T. Kimball, what happened to be the first, like, principal, female principal?

80
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:49,000
Okay.

81
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:50,000
And Dordi Caldwell.

82
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:55,000
And what do you remember about her?

83
00:05:55,000 --> 00:06:01,000
I remember that she was very strict, and that you had to follow policies.

84
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:03,000
I remember that quite well.

85
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:04,000
Okay.

86
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:08,000
And, um, were there any other teachers?

87
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:14,000
Well, I had Miss Rimmel's as a home economics teacher.

88
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:15,000
Okay.

89
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:20,000
Miss Thelma French, who was also a home economics teacher.

90
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:29,000
Miss Olive Rogers was my English teacher, and many others.

91
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:30,000
Okay.

92
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:33,000
So, what do you remember about the instruction of the teachers?

93
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:37,000
Were they, I mean, were they very protective of the students or did they?

94
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:44,000
You know, you said they would dissonant with disciplinarians and others, while others were mentors.

95
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:45,000
And so forth.

96
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:48,000
You know, we don't have problems that they have.

97
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:49,000
Right.

98
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:51,000
You know, we didn't have the problems that they have today.

99
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:52,000
Right.

100
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:54,000
Thank God.

101
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:59,000
But, um, yes, they discipline us.

102
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:01,000
We did things that were wrong.

103
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:10,000
But we didn't have, well, we could have corporate punishment, but it wasn't brutal or abusive,

104
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:12,000
you know, in any way.

105
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:14,000
And it was never a type of person.

106
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:17,000
Well, no, it just fortunate that I wasn't really.

107
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:18,000
Okay.

108
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:23,000
While I was there, I served on many committees.

109
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:31,000
I was the editor-in-chief of the high school annual, my senior year.

110
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:32,000
Okay.

111
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:41,000
And, um, what other, what, do you remember any of your close friends from school that you,

112
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:45,000
did you stay in touch with, stayed close to them?

113
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:51,000
Yes, I have a very different, um, Vashti Stubbs.

114
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:52,000
Vashti Stubbs?

115
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:54,000
We were very close friends.

116
00:07:54,000 --> 00:08:02,000
I remember when I was giving the, um, salutatorian.

117
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:10,000
And as I sat there waiting for my turn, I was so nervous.

118
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:12,000
And she took my hand.

119
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:19,000
And when I got up, I guess I did just fine because I wasn't as nervous.

120
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:20,000
Okay.

121
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:24,000
So when you graduate, so you, you, you're going to become the salutatorian of Madison High School,

122
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:30,000
and you graduate, um, did you know at that point that you wanted to be a teacher?

123
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:31,000
Or...

124
00:08:31,000 --> 00:08:38,000
I think, I think I always wanted to follow in the footsteps of those who taught me.

125
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:39,000
Okay.

126
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:41,000
And you decided on a teacher?

127
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:43,000
And I decided on being a teacher.

128
00:08:43,000 --> 00:08:44,000
Okay.

129
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:47,000
Uh, at one point, I really wanted to be a writer.

130
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:50,000
I wanted to write novels, fiction novels.

131
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:53,000
But that didn't work out too well.

132
00:08:53,000 --> 00:08:57,000
Who was some of your favorite novels that you were reading the time, do you recall?

133
00:08:57,000 --> 00:09:00,000
At that time, my goodness.

134
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:04,000
And they were right on the tip of my tongue to hear, think about it.

135
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:05,000
That's okay.

136
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:09,000
Um, now you decided to go to Fisk University who, um, directed you and...

137
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:18,000
Well, I had a teacher, um, that thought that Fisk might be a good school, um, little arts.

138
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:19,000
A little arts school.

139
00:09:19,000 --> 00:09:28,000
And, um, I had to consider it, you know, a great deal financially, you know, even though

140
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:31,000
it wasn't an expensive at schools or now.

141
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:32,000
Right.

142
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:37,000
And I had to go to any of my parents made it possible for me to attend.

143
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:38,000
Okay.

144
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:42,000
So this is the first time you're away from home and you're in Nashville, Tennessee.

145
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:43,000
It was.

146
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:44,000
Well, at that age, it was the first time.

147
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:45,000
Right.

148
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:46,000
Yes.

149
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:47,000
And what was that experience like?

150
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:48,000
Were you?

151
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:55,000
Well, you know, my first year of there, in fact, it's amazing that when I arrived on the

152
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:59,000
campus of Fisk, you wouldn't believe it.

153
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:10,000
Almost the first day, they thrust", um, um, a petition in my hand.

154
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:13,000
They wanted to get rid of a teacher.

155
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:14,000
Oh, wow.

156
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:20,000
And I didn't even know the teacher had never met her, but they were so persuasive that I

157
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:21,000
signed it.

158
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:26,000
But fortunately, they didn't succeed.

159
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:29,000
And later, she was the best teacher that I ever had.

160
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:30,000
Oh, wow.

161
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:31,000
Who was the teacher?

162
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:32,000
I do.

163
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:34,000
What did she teach?

164
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:39,000
Well, she was in the, or she was in the, um, little theater.

165
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:40,000
Okay.

166
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:43,000
Because I did belong to the little theater while I was there.

167
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:44,000
Okay.

168
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:45,000
I took creative writing.

169
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:46,000
Yes.

170
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:47,000
Okay.

171
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:48,000
Okay.

172
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:50,000
What other, um, activities at Fisk?

173
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:54,000
Were you involved in?

174
00:10:54,000 --> 00:10:57,000
Well, mainly the writing, other than my sorority.

175
00:10:57,000 --> 00:10:58,000
Okay.

176
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:06,000
But mainly, um, the creative writing activities, um, I did place with the little theater.

177
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:17,000
In fact, my senior year, um, my grade came from directing a play that was written by one of my teachers.

178
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:18,000
Okay.

179
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:19,000
Okay.

180
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:21,000
Um, um, okay.

181
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:26,000
Um, I'm not begging you that though.

182
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:27,000
You know, okay.

183
00:11:27,000 --> 00:11:31,000
Um, so, um, after, after Fisk, where, where did you go?

184
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:32,000
What did you decide to do?

185
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:33,000
You graduated in 1950.

186
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:34,000
I take, I take it.

187
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:42,000
Well, you know, before I, um, I, uh, finished Fisk, I really went into the service.

188
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:44,000
I stayed two years in the service.

189
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:45,000
Okay.

190
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:48,000
I, I got married while I was in the service.

191
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:49,000
You married.

192
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:50,000
Who did you marry?

193
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:52,000
You see, I married two Jenkins.

194
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:53,000
Two Jenkins.

195
00:11:53,000 --> 00:11:54,000
Right.

196
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:55,000
Roscoe Jenkins.

197
00:11:55,000 --> 00:11:56,000
Okay.

198
00:11:56,000 --> 00:12:02,000
And, um, so, in, what was your experience like in the service?

199
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:05,000
Well, basic training.

200
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:06,000
Basic training.

201
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:12,000
Well, something that I had to really adjust to and get used to that, (basic training) took place in Virginia.

202
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:20,000
And then I went to, uh, Fort Dix, which was, (Fort Dix's) Special Services.

203
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:27,000
And I was transferred there in station at Fort Custer.

204
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:29,000
In Michigan.

205
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:31,000
And I didn't have any problems.

206
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:33,000
So, was it, was it segregated at all?

207
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:34,000
Still was segregated?

208
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:35,000
Oh, yeah.

209
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:36,000
Still segregated.

210
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:37,000
Okay.

211
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:38,000
And you know, I had no problems.

212
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:40,000
Um, so you decided to leave.

213
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:42,000
You decided to stay after?

214
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:43,000
Yes.

215
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:45,000
I had my daughter Sherry.

216
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:51,000
And, um, I knew then that I had a responsibility that I had to have a job.

217
00:12:51,000 --> 00:12:52,000
Right.

218
00:12:52,000 --> 00:12:55,000
So, I decided, well, my mother's training.

219
00:12:55,000 --> 00:12:56,000
Education.

220
00:12:56,000 --> 00:12:57,000
Right.

221
00:12:57,000 --> 00:12:59,000
And I was only half through at Fisk.

222
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:02,000
So, I decided to go back and finish.

223
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:03,000
Okay.

224
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:04,000
Oh, okay.

225
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:05,000
Okay.

226
00:13:05,000 --> 00:13:08,000
So, after you finished, you decided to move back to Albany?

227
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:10,000
I was a little bit nervous.

228
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:12,000
Now, um, what brought you back here?

229
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:14,000
And that was Roscoe from, from Albany as well?

230
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:16,000
No, he was from North Carolina.

231
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:17,000
Okay.

232
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:22,000
But he, uh, went overseas.

233
00:13:22,000 --> 00:13:23,000
Okay.

234
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:26,000
And after that, you know, we divorced.

235
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:27,000
Okay.

236
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:33,000
I came home and a few years later, I married again.

237
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:34,000
Okay.

238
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:39,000
And when you first came back, did you immediately pursue a job in the school system?

239
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:40,000
I did.

240
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:43,000
Uh, but what happened when I graduated from Fisk?

241
00:13:43,000 --> 00:13:45,000
I had a second year of certificate.

242
00:13:45,000 --> 00:13:46,000
Okay.

243
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:52,000
And the supervisor here promised me a job, but she was an elementary supervisor,

244
00:13:52,000 --> 00:13:56,000
which meant that I would have had to have had, uh, elementary certificate.

245
00:13:56,000 --> 00:13:57,000
Okay.

246
00:13:57,000 --> 00:14:02,000
So, I went over to Albany State University University, spent a whole summer trying to get an elementary certificate.

247
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:11,000
But, um, when I finished, the supervisor had to, you know, fill the job on time.

248
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:12,000
Right.

249
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:13,000
She couldn't just wait for me.

250
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:14,000
Right.

251
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:23,000
And so, uh, my pastor, Rev. James Grant, he was a principal at East Baker High School.

252
00:14:23,000 --> 00:14:24,000
Okay.

253
00:14:24,000 --> 00:14:25,000
He promised me the job.

254
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:26,000
Okay.

255
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:30,000
So, talk about the job.

256
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:34,000
When you came into it, was it everything that you expected?

257
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:35,000
Oh, my goodness.

258
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:38,000
Well, with the solid earliest challenges that you faced.

259
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:50,000
It was at Baker County, that I learned the power, white power, what white power could do.

260
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:58,000
And I knew that, that as soon as I could get out of Baker County, I wanted to, um,

261
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:01,000
two incidents happened.

262
00:15:01,000 --> 00:15:08,000
One involved a young, a young man who somehow another got involved in some incident over a weekend.

263
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:13,000
It wasn't anything that required police.

264
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:19,000
But anyway, there were students who somehow took care of him and carried him home.

265
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:26,000
But early that morning, somehow the information had gotten to the white supervisor.

266
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:32,000
And she came over to the school and she walked into his room and she told them,

267
00:15:32,000 --> 00:15:34,000
pack up.

268
00:15:34,000 --> 00:15:37,000
This is your last day.

269
00:15:37,000 --> 00:15:38,000
And it was.

270
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:40,000
He had no recourse.

271
00:15:40,000 --> 00:15:42,000
No one to go to.

272
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:48,000
In fact, her husband was the, uh, superintendent of the, uh,

273
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:53,000
of a Baker County school superintendent of Baker County.

274
00:15:53,000 --> 00:16:00,000
And so that young man lost his job without being able to defend himself.

275
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:05,000
And then the next incident that happened really happened at the end of my turn, then.

276
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:11,000
And I think it was also the year that the Supreme Court ruled on desegregation and.

277
00:16:11,000 --> 00:16:14,000
Yeah, in public schools.

278
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:26,000
And, um, she came over to the school and assembled all the black teachers in the room.

279
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:36,000
And she talked, well, I don't know how long about how wrong it was for us to be together.

280
00:16:36,000 --> 00:16:41,000
And she had teachers that stood up and agreed with her.

281
00:16:41,000 --> 00:16:42,000
It's a black teacher.

282
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:49,000
But I kept my seat because I knew that I couldn't agree with all that she was saying.

283
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:56,000
And then at the end of her speech, she said this.

284
00:16:56,000 --> 00:17:00,000
She said they may make us go to school with you.

285
00:17:00,000 --> 00:17:05,000
But I would never invite one of you to my home.

286
00:17:05,000 --> 00:17:10,000
I was through with Baker County.

287
00:17:10,000 --> 00:17:17,000
So you left Baker County after, um, one year and you came to.

288
00:17:17,000 --> 00:17:21,000
I came to, uh, Albany, uh, at Carver Junior High School.

289
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:22,000
Carb of.

290
00:17:22,000 --> 00:17:27,000
A teacher at Carver Junior High School.

291
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:33,000
And how was that, how was, was it different, um, how different was it from Baker County?

292
00:17:33,000 --> 00:17:34,000
Or was there much to say?

293
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:41,000
Well, I tell you one thing, it was different in the environment because actually when I taught in Baker County,

294
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:44,000
it was like a barracks, a army barracks.

295
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:45,000
Okay.

296
00:17:45,000 --> 00:17:49,000
So it was quite different in the actual school building was in another place.

297
00:17:49,000 --> 00:17:55,000
Well, and then I can't say that Dougherty County was any different because they were adding on.

298
00:17:55,000 --> 00:18:02,000
But at that time, they had army barracks in the back of the building.

299
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:07,000
And for about two months, I think I had to teach in, in the barracks.

300
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:09,000
I didn't have a room.

301
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:14,000
And then they moved me into the, uh, Jason building to it.

302
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:15,000
Okay.

303
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:17,000
So, so, did you have chalkboards?

304
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:18,000
I mean, what did you have there?

305
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:22,000
Yeah, we had chalkboards and racers and, you know, yeah, we had.

306
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:24,000
But still hand me down second books.

307
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:25,000
Oh, yes.

308
00:18:25,000 --> 00:18:29,000
I don't think it was too different, you know, in that aspect.

309
00:18:29,000 --> 00:18:30,000
Okay.

310
00:18:30,000 --> 00:18:31,000
How were the students?

311
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:33,000
I mean, did you have many problems out there?

312
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:35,000
Well, I had good students, some of them.

313
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:39,000
You know, I look at what is happening today.

314
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:41,000
We have gangs.

315
00:18:41,000 --> 00:18:42,000
Right.

316
00:18:42,000 --> 00:18:47,000
But you know, then we might have one person that could upset the whole school.

317
00:18:47,000 --> 00:18:52,000
And, um, it was different then.

318
00:18:52,000 --> 00:18:53,000
Okay.

319
00:18:53,000 --> 00:18:56,000
And we could discipline then.

320
00:18:56,000 --> 00:18:59,000
And this is what we need now.

321
00:18:59,000 --> 00:19:00,000
Okay.

322
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:06,000
So, this is probably mid-1950s, 55-56s that we're talking about.

323
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:09,000
And, um, what do you know about?

324
00:19:09,000 --> 00:19:12,000
Yeah, we're talking about 58-59, you know.

325
00:19:12,000 --> 00:19:13,000
So, this is what things...

326
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:16,000
Just a little before the movement actually started.

327
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:17,000
Right.

328
00:19:17,000 --> 00:19:24,000
So, what was taking place in the black community that before the Albany movement really took off?

329
00:19:24,000 --> 00:19:27,000
You know, a lot of things were being done quietly.

330
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:32,000
We were making the kind of noise that we made during the Albany movement.

331
00:19:32,000 --> 00:19:39,000
But I recall that a group of men that had a Criterion Club.

332
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:51,000
And they had gone down to the City Commission and requested that they organize a BIRacial Committee.

333
00:19:51,000 --> 00:19:55,000
So that some of the problems that Black said could be resolved.

334
00:19:55,000 --> 00:19:56,000
Right.

335
00:19:57,000 --> 00:19:59,000
They were turned down.

336
00:19:59,000 --> 00:20:03,000
And even Dr. William G. Anderson, who was president of Albany movement,

337
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:09,000
he lived in an area where when it rained sometimes they couldn't even get out of the front door.

338
00:20:09,000 --> 00:20:13,000
And he had gone down and talked about the situation.

339
00:20:13,000 --> 00:20:15,000
But he too was refused.

340
00:20:15,000 --> 00:20:20,000
And even after the movement was organized at the very beginning,

341
00:20:21,000 --> 00:20:26,000
they had three representatives that went before the City Commissioners.

342
00:20:26,000 --> 00:20:32,000
And asked them to organize a BIRacial Committee.

343
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:40,000
And they were told that they had no way of doing that.

344
00:20:40,000 --> 00:20:41,000
So the White...

345
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:43,000
The staff is just refused.

346
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:52,000
If everything was all White as for as the City Commissioners and the government, so to speak.

347
00:20:52,000 --> 00:20:58,000
So from my understanding, some of the earliest things that these people involved from Criterion Club,

348
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:05,000
one of the things that they pointed out that they wanted to discuss was the portrayal of Blacks in the Albany Herald newspaper.

349
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:10,000
How all the news that was being reported in the Albany Herald was all negative.

350
00:21:10,000 --> 00:21:13,000
And it was never any positive news about Blacks.

351
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:20,000
Well, you must remember too that the Albany Herald was owned by a White man,

352
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:24,000
a radio station owned by a White man.

353
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:31,000
So everything naturally he dictated his way.

354
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:37,000
So that, I guess, is why there are complaints even there.

355
00:21:37,000 --> 00:21:38,000
We ignored.

356
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:39,000
Right.

357
00:21:39,000 --> 00:21:45,000
Did you read the Albany Herald or listen to the logo radio stations at all?

358
00:21:45,000 --> 00:21:46,000
Oh, yes.

359
00:21:46,000 --> 00:21:48,000
What else could you do?

360
00:21:48,000 --> 00:21:50,000
You don't even want to hear any news at all.

361
00:21:50,000 --> 00:21:56,000
So yes, I read the Albany Herald and I listened to the TV station.

362
00:21:57,000 --> 00:22:02,000
So were there any other sources of news outside of Albany, like Black news papers?

363
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:10,000
Oh, yes, we had the Southwest Georgian that was edited by Southwest Georgian.

364
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:20,000
And any other newspapers outside of the Southwest, like National Black news papers coming into the community?

365
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:25,000
No, unless now there were people who subscribed, you know.

366
00:22:26,000 --> 00:22:32,000
And they were like, I think they were Americans, something of that sort.

367
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:36,000
But you had to subscribe to those papers.

368
00:22:36,000 --> 00:22:43,000
So let's talk a little bit about the Albany movement itself and how you can to be involved.

369
00:22:43,000 --> 00:22:48,000
Did someone approach you or did you just make the decision that you were going to listen?

370
00:22:48,000 --> 00:22:54,000
Take me back to that moment when the movement was finally here in Albany.

371
00:22:55,000 --> 00:23:00,000
And when you decided that you were going to participate?

372
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:07,000
Well, you know, you hear a lot of rumors about things that are going to happen before they happen.

373
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:15,000
And so I had heard that, you know, about the movement and how it was going to be organized, that kind of thing.

374
00:23:15,000 --> 00:23:19,000
So I went to the first mass meeting.

375
00:23:19,000 --> 00:23:21,000
Where was this mass meeting?

376
00:23:21,000 --> 00:23:28,000
This was held at the Mount Zion Baptist Church under Rev. James Grant.

377
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:33,000
What do you remember about that meeting?

378
00:23:33,000 --> 00:23:36,000
I remember the crowds.

379
00:23:36,000 --> 00:23:39,000
I remember the singing.

380
00:23:39,000 --> 00:23:42,000
I remember the crying.

381
00:23:42,000 --> 00:23:48,000
And people just making an all kind of pleas, you know.

382
00:23:48,000 --> 00:23:51,000
And it was an emotional meeting.

383
00:23:51,000 --> 00:23:59,000
People banded together and singing along with, well, they weren't called Freedom Singers at that particular time.

384
00:23:59,000 --> 00:24:11,000
But they were the leaders of Freedom of Songs like Charles Sherrod and Bernice Johnson Reagon, and Rutha Mae Harris.

385
00:24:11,000 --> 00:24:15,000
And I was moved.

386
00:24:15,000 --> 00:24:20,000
Because I wanted all of the, you can't take another of my life.

387
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:25,000
You can't go to this restaurant.

388
00:24:25,000 --> 00:24:30,000
You can't eat in this restaurant.

389
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:38,000
I wanted all of that out of my life, not only for myself, but I wanted it out for my children.

390
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:46,000
I wanted them to have a better quality of life than I had as far as segregation was concerned.

391
00:24:46,000 --> 00:24:57,000
So, after that meeting, I imagine one or two more meetings, why did you walk or came down?

392
00:24:57,000 --> 00:25:07,000
And he said, we need some help in the office that was set up in Dr. William G. Anderson's house, but Martin Luther King Jr.

393
00:25:07,000 --> 00:25:16,000
And so I volunteered and I worked there, you know, for the time that Dr. King had his office there.

394
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:20,000
Okay. What types of things were you doing in the office?

395
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:25,000
Well, I was answering the telephone, taking messages. And it was awesome sometimes.

396
00:25:25,000 --> 00:25:31,000
It was awesome because Dr. King would walk here, throw a number in my hand.

397
00:25:31,000 --> 00:25:36,000
And he said, I want to talk to such a person. They're famous people.

398
00:25:36,000 --> 00:25:40,000
And he would want me to contact him.

399
00:25:40,000 --> 00:25:50,000
Once he put a number in my hand that was for, oh, this calypso singer, God, I can't say that.

400
00:25:50,000 --> 00:25:52,000
Harry Belafonte.

401
00:25:52,000 --> 00:25:56,000
Harry Belafonte. I couldn't believe that I was going to talk to Harry Belafonte.

402
00:25:56,000 --> 00:26:04,000
But I dialed the number. It's sure enough I didn't because I was told that he wasn't in, but that Dr. King would get the message.

403
00:26:04,000 --> 00:26:05,000
Okay.

404
00:26:05,000 --> 00:26:12,000
So there were meetings that Dr. King had with just females.

405
00:26:12,000 --> 00:26:17,000
He believed that women were the movers and shakers of the world.

406
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:23,000
And I learned that he was a listener. He might pose a question.

407
00:26:23,000 --> 00:26:31,000
But then he would stand back and listen to the comments that were made.

408
00:26:31,000 --> 00:26:38,000
So that was quite an experience for me.

409
00:26:38,000 --> 00:26:47,000
But as I sat in meeting after meeting and listened to the people who went to jail,

410
00:26:47,000 --> 00:26:55,000
and then they came back to the meetings and described how they were treated in jail.

411
00:26:55,000 --> 00:27:02,000
And I guess I began to think, my goodness, they know Martin Luther King Jr was here.

412
00:27:02,000 --> 00:27:06,000
And they know Sherrod because he's everywhere.

413
00:27:06,000 --> 00:27:12,000
I said, but you have a lot of people. People will never know what happened to them.

414
00:27:13,000 --> 00:27:20,000
How they were treated, what they sacrificed for equality.

415
00:27:20,000 --> 00:27:25,000
And so I began to just take notes of what some of them were saying.

416
00:27:25,000 --> 00:27:31,000
Sometimes I would write on fans, I'd run out of paper in my purse.

417
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:39,000
But I just thought that there should be something about what was happening here for future generations.

418
00:27:39,000 --> 00:27:44,000
And so, maybe I was thinking about children who needed to know.

419
00:27:44,000 --> 00:27:48,000
And so I wrote the book.

420
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:56,000
Okay. So, do you still have those feelings about,

421
00:27:56,000 --> 00:28:03,000
oh, do you have those fans that you still wrote notes on? Those fans?

422
00:28:03,000 --> 00:28:08,000
You said you wrote notes of?

423
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:13,000
I've been trying to go through things that I have in my attic.

424
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:21,000
I'm trying to put them all in a box so that one day somebody might give them to the museum.

425
00:28:21,000 --> 00:28:28,000
So, I think we could probably arrange that happen this weekend.

426
00:28:28,000 --> 00:28:33,000
So, I guess I want to back up a little bit about what I know about Southwest Georgia

427
00:28:33,000 --> 00:28:36,000
and teachers who got involved in local movements.

428
00:28:36,000 --> 00:28:42,000
They were often threatened with intimidation and the threat of losing their jobs.

429
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:43,000
Did that ever happen to you?

430
00:28:43,000 --> 00:28:47,000
Well, nobody officially threatened my job.

431
00:28:47,000 --> 00:28:54,000
But we knew that if we were arrested, that we would be fired.

432
00:28:54,000 --> 00:29:02,000
And it was also rumored that they sent people to even check car tags at the mass meetings.

433
00:29:02,000 --> 00:29:05,000
So, we were all aware of that.

434
00:29:05,000 --> 00:29:10,000
So, it was that decision that you made not to march and get arrested?

435
00:29:10,000 --> 00:29:15,000
Even though there was one time when I thought I would.

436
00:29:15,000 --> 00:29:22,000
We were in Molles Island Baptist Church and Rev. James Grant had just finished the sermon for that Sunday.

437
00:29:22,000 --> 00:29:24,000
And he made the statement.

438
00:29:24,000 --> 00:29:31,000
He said that after this said, I'm going to do something.

439
00:29:31,000 --> 00:29:34,000
I'm going to do it for myself.

440
00:29:34,000 --> 00:29:37,000
And I can do it by myself.

441
00:29:37,000 --> 00:29:40,000
And he stepped out of that pool pit.

442
00:29:40,000 --> 00:29:46,000
And well, people, you know, they weren't going to let them do anything by themselves.

443
00:29:46,000 --> 00:29:49,000
So, there were several people who got up.

444
00:29:49,000 --> 00:29:52,000
And I don't know what moved me.

445
00:29:52,000 --> 00:29:55,000
I had my four-year-old son in my arms.

446
00:29:55,000 --> 00:29:59,000
And I got up and got in line.

447
00:29:59,000 --> 00:30:02,000
But when I got to the door, my husband was standing there.

448
00:30:02,000 --> 00:30:06,000
And he gently pulled me out of the line.

449
00:30:06,000 --> 00:30:09,000
And I guess I lost my spirit.

450
00:30:09,000 --> 00:30:16,000
And you know, that particular day, Chief Laurie Pritchett had decided not to arrest anybody.

451
00:30:16,000 --> 00:30:18,000
That could have been your moment.

452
00:30:18,000 --> 00:30:20,000
That could have marched.

453
00:30:20,000 --> 00:30:24,000
So, I imagine you knew a lot of other teachers who did any of the teachers who marched.

454
00:30:24,000 --> 00:30:26,000
Oh, yes.

455
00:30:26,000 --> 00:30:36,000
Now, when they started our integration in the school,

456
00:30:36,000 --> 00:30:42,000
there were teachers who were, of course, sent into the old white schools.

457
00:30:42,000 --> 00:30:50,000
And some of the experiences that they had were very humiliating, not so long.

458
00:30:50,000 --> 00:30:51,000
Okay.

459
00:30:51,000 --> 00:30:58,000
Because some of them, in one school, the black teachers had a whole home by themselves.

460
00:30:58,000 --> 00:31:01,000
Nobody teaches there at all.

461
00:31:01,000 --> 00:31:10,000
And when grading time came, in some schools, they would have to carry the report cards to the principal

462
00:31:10,000 --> 00:31:15,000
so that he could see whether the white students had been given the proper grades.

463
00:31:15,000 --> 00:31:21,000
So there were a lot of humiliating incidents that occurred.

464
00:31:21,000 --> 00:31:26,000
So you were getting ready to talk about your decision to write the book,

465
00:31:26,000 --> 00:31:30,000
Open Themselves (Mary Frances Jenkins, self-published) — title verification flagged: A Pictorial History of the Albany Civil Rights Movement: A Pictorial History of the Albany Civil Rights Movement about the Albany movement.

466
00:31:30,000 --> 00:31:32,000
What prompted you to want to do that?

467
00:31:32,000 --> 00:31:35,000
I mean, you always mentioned that you wanted to be a novelist.

468
00:31:35,000 --> 00:31:41,000
I wanted to be a writer, and I can imagine that is why I was prompted to take notes

469
00:31:41,000 --> 00:31:47,000
about what was happening.

470
00:31:47,000 --> 00:31:53,000
I wanted it to be a book, but at that time I really wasn't thinking of it being a book.

471
00:31:53,000 --> 00:31:55,000
What did you really want to do?

472
00:31:55,000 --> 00:32:00,000
When did you start the idea of even doing it?

473
00:32:00,000 --> 00:32:07,000
Well, what happened was my daughter, she's a sea-steed.

474
00:32:07,000 --> 00:32:11,000
But she knew I had all this material.

475
00:32:11,000 --> 00:32:15,000
And she kept saying, why don't you put it together in a book?

476
00:32:15,000 --> 00:32:22,000
And of course, I hesitated, you know, for a decade, I guess I should say.

477
00:32:22,000 --> 00:32:27,000
And she passed.

478
00:32:27,000 --> 00:32:33,000
And I guess the one thing was in my mind was what she said to me.

479
00:32:33,000 --> 00:32:39,000
And so that is why I started working on trying to put it together.

480
00:32:39,000 --> 00:32:43,000
Talk about the process of putting it together.

481
00:32:43,000 --> 00:32:46,000
Was it tough putting the book together?

482
00:32:46,000 --> 00:32:51,000
Well, once I had the organizational technique for it,

483
00:32:51,000 --> 00:32:58,000
and I could just go through all the material and place them according to the outline that I had.

484
00:32:58,000 --> 00:33:02,000
So having the material is what's important, you know.

485
00:33:02,000 --> 00:33:04,000
And I had that.

486
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:08,000
So it turned out to be a fairly easy job.

487
00:33:08,000 --> 00:33:14,000
The only problem that I had was that I didn't know anything about publishing a book.

488
00:33:14,000 --> 00:33:18,000
Didn't really know who to go to, to talk to.

489
00:33:18,000 --> 00:33:25,000
And what I saw was a company that had done religious books.

490
00:33:25,000 --> 00:33:28,000
It was out of Columbus, Georgia.

491
00:33:28,000 --> 00:33:33,000
And so my husband and I both decided after I had everything together,

492
00:33:33,000 --> 00:33:37,000
we would take it to this company, which we did.

493
00:33:37,000 --> 00:33:42,000
The publisher was really was fantastic, I can say.

494
00:33:42,000 --> 00:33:50,000
What I hadn't anticipated was the people behind the publisher, you know, the copy seller,

495
00:33:50,000 --> 00:33:59,000
who was, I can see now, white lady, who I guess didn't like all of this material that was in the book.

496
00:33:59,000 --> 00:34:06,000
And I kept finding arrows, you know, and I would go to the publisher and tell them.

497
00:34:06,000 --> 00:34:16,000
And well, I had to pay for every mistake that was there, as if I guess it were mine.

498
00:34:16,000 --> 00:34:24,000
And so finally what happened, I always say God's deputy.

499
00:34:24,000 --> 00:34:29,000
Because I sold out of the first edition.

500
00:34:29,000 --> 00:34:37,000
And the second edition, we picked up the books like on a Friday.

501
00:34:37,000 --> 00:34:42,000
And the company was closed now that weekend.

502
00:34:42,000 --> 00:34:48,000
We had a book signing that Saturday, or Sunday, I can't remember which one of those dates.

503
00:34:48,000 --> 00:34:58,000
But when we went through the book, we found a page where, you know, on the page where they're going to put a picture,

504
00:34:58,000 --> 00:35:02,000
where the picture goes, they have a blank spot.

505
00:35:02,000 --> 00:35:07,000
And the directions at the top says, drop him.

506
00:35:07,000 --> 00:35:11,000
And they didn't drop the picture and print all those books.

507
00:35:11,000 --> 00:35:13,000
Oh wow.

508
00:35:13,000 --> 00:35:20,000
So I had a decision to make, well or not, I would accept the book, you know, in my mind.

509
00:35:20,000 --> 00:35:26,000
And whether I would just not have the book signing.

510
00:35:26,000 --> 00:35:31,000
But everything was so close until I said, well, I decided I would have the book signing.

511
00:35:31,000 --> 00:35:34,000
I would explain about the mistake.

512
00:35:34,000 --> 00:35:42,000
And once it was corrected, then the persons that bought books would get the corrected copy.

513
00:35:42,000 --> 00:35:48,000
So that Monday morning, early in my husband and I went to Columbus, Georgia.

514
00:35:48,000 --> 00:35:53,000
And well, the publisher knew that it was his mistake.

515
00:35:53,000 --> 00:35:57,000
And that he would have to account for it.

516
00:35:57,000 --> 00:36:03,000
He made all kind of offers to us so that he wouldn't have to redo the whole book.

517
00:36:03,000 --> 00:36:06,000
But my husband would accept it.

518
00:36:06,000 --> 00:36:12,000
So finally, he said, okay, I'll redo the book.

519
00:36:12,000 --> 00:36:18,000
But when the book was printed, he didn't use second edition.

520
00:36:18,000 --> 00:36:22,000
He used third edition.

521
00:36:22,000 --> 00:36:25,000
Okay. So how did the community respond to your book?

522
00:36:25,000 --> 00:36:27,000
I mean, the readers who were interested.

523
00:36:27,000 --> 00:36:30,000
I can't say anything about the book.

524
00:36:30,000 --> 00:36:33,000
They were fantastic, really.

525
00:36:33,000 --> 00:36:36,000
That is why I guess the first edition went so far.

526
00:36:36,000 --> 00:36:43,000
And then we got into, well, really, the fourth edition.

527
00:36:43,000 --> 00:36:50,000
Okay. So what, I mean, you've talked a little bit about the process of creating the book and getting it published.

528
00:36:50,000 --> 00:36:54,000
Do you think it accomplished? What were you trying to accomplish with the book?

529
00:36:54,000 --> 00:36:58,000
Well, mainly to get information out.

530
00:36:58,000 --> 00:37:05,000
I wish every black family had a copy of the book for their children.

531
00:37:05,000 --> 00:37:12,000
But I tell you now, since then, I've thought about it.

532
00:37:12,000 --> 00:37:17,000
There's a lot of writing in the book, even though it says a pictorial history.

533
00:37:17,000 --> 00:37:20,000
And children like to look at pictures.

534
00:37:20,000 --> 00:37:22,000
Could you hold the book up?

535
00:37:22,000 --> 00:37:25,000
And children like to look at pictures.

536
00:37:25,000 --> 00:37:28,000
But they're not that fun and reading.

537
00:37:28,000 --> 00:37:29,000
Right.

538
00:37:29,000 --> 00:37:34,000
And since then, I have discovered that they're like poetry.

539
00:37:34,000 --> 00:37:40,000
So what I'm doing now is a book on, it's really on all the movement.

540
00:37:40,000 --> 00:37:42,000
But it's done in poetry.

541
00:37:42,000 --> 00:37:45,000
Okay. And these are all be poems by you?

542
00:37:45,000 --> 00:37:46,000
Yes.

543
00:37:46,000 --> 00:37:48,000
Okay. Okay.

544
00:37:48,000 --> 00:37:54,000
So the Albany movement, then, it's impact on the community.

545
00:37:54,000 --> 00:37:59,000
Talk about that. How do you, do you, do you think it was successful?

546
00:37:59,000 --> 00:38:04,000
Do you think there are some areas that are naturally, you know,

547
00:38:04,000 --> 00:38:08,000
there's some work that still needs to be done?

548
00:38:08,000 --> 00:38:10,000
What do you think it accomplished?

549
00:38:10,000 --> 00:38:14,000
Well, I wonder how long it would have taken us to get where we are today.

550
00:38:14,000 --> 00:38:17,000
Had it not been for all been a movement.

551
00:38:17,000 --> 00:38:25,000
When I walk in stores or walking bags and seeing black people behind the desk,

552
00:38:25,000 --> 00:38:27,000
this is what we accomplished.

553
00:38:27,000 --> 00:38:28,000
Okay.

554
00:38:28,000 --> 00:38:32,000
We might have gotten this far, but I don't know how long it would have taken

555
00:38:32,000 --> 00:38:37,000
without the movement, you know, pressuring these issues.

556
00:38:37,000 --> 00:38:42,000
And so I give credit to the movement,

557
00:38:42,000 --> 00:38:45,000
of where we are today.

558
00:38:45,000 --> 00:38:53,000
And we must remember, too, that the journey is not over.

559
00:38:53,000 --> 00:38:59,000
You know, I look at, we've come so capitalistic, too.

560
00:38:59,000 --> 00:39:08,000
And I think of Martin Luther King Jr and the legacy that he left us

561
00:39:08,000 --> 00:39:15,000
of service and preparing young people for the future,

562
00:39:15,000 --> 00:39:19,000
because it's the paternalists in their hands now.

563
00:39:19,000 --> 00:39:25,000
And they must know what to do and how to do the things that need to be done.

564
00:39:25,000 --> 00:39:31,000
You know, I was thinking about those young people who went into the bus station

565
00:39:31,000 --> 00:39:34,000
that really was the beginning of the movement.

566
00:39:34,000 --> 00:39:37,000
They didn't go there to break logs.

567
00:39:37,000 --> 00:39:41,000
You know, they went there to enforce logs.

568
00:39:41,000 --> 00:39:44,000
The ICC (Interstate Commerce Commission) regulation banning segregation in interstate-bus terminals.

569
00:39:44,000 --> 00:39:50,000
And those six girls that went into all been a high school.

570
00:39:50,000 --> 00:39:57,000
Simply because CB King struggled eight long years after the Supreme Court ruled

571
00:39:57,000 --> 00:40:01,000
on desegregation in public school.

572
00:40:01,000 --> 00:40:08,000
So, and then think now, the laws that helped us then,

573
00:40:08,000 --> 00:40:12,000
are the laws that are being challenged now.

574
00:40:12,000 --> 00:40:16,000
That's correct. Very true.

575
00:40:16,000 --> 00:40:18,000
Okay. All right. Well, I thank you.

576
00:40:18,000 --> 00:40:25,000
Is there anything else you would like to add to your story?

577
00:40:25,000 --> 00:40:27,000
Well, I think I've said it, oh.

578
00:40:27,000 --> 00:40:28,000
Thank you. Okay.

579
00:40:28,000 --> 00:40:33,000
Well, thank you so much, Mr. Jenkins, for offering us your time to share

580
00:40:33,000 --> 00:40:36,000
with you in the Civil Rights History Project.

581
00:40:36,000 --> 00:40:39,000
Well, thank you. That was great.

582
00:40:39,000 --> 00:40:42,000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress

583
00:40:42,000 --> 00:40:47,000
and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

